               <msContents>
                  <summary>This second of three volumes of an incomplete, undated set, of the <title
                        xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_4665">Tārīkh-i Alfī</title> (Millenial
                     History) by <persName key="person_61243125"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/61243125/" xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard"
                        >Aḥmad Tattavī (d. 1588)</persName>, together with <ref
                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7415"><idno>Persian MS
                           904</idno></ref>. It summarizes events of the prior millenium and
                     presents a general history of Turkic and Mongol rulers with this volume
                     spanning the years <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1158">533–770 AH
                        (1158–1368 CE)</date>.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_903-item1" defective="true">
                     <author key="person_61243125" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/61243125/">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Tattavī, Aḥmad, d.
                           1588</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">ملا احمد تتوی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_4665">Tārīkh-i Alfī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_4665">تاریخ الفی</title>
                     <!--  <incipit xml:lang="ar" type="basmalla"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio
                           1b):</locus>
                     </incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="233a" to="233a"> برگ ۲۳۳ر (folio 233a):</locus>
                     </explicit> -->
                     <colophon>No colophon</colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Textblock of cross-grained, externally sized and polished,
                           cream-coloured <material>paper</material> probably handmade in the
                              <placeName cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                              key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</placeName> with ~14 laid
                           lines per 20 mm and 115 microns thick.</support>
                        <extent>
                           <measure unit="folio" quantity="271">271 folios, 2 flyleaves (ff. i + 271
                              + i)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>337</height>
                              <width>253</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>243</height>
                              <width>165</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>

                        <foliation xml:id="modern">Partially foliated in pencilled Arabic numerals
                           on the upper-left corners of the a sides.</foliation>

                        <collation> Undetermined. <catchwords>Catchwords throughout most of the
                              lower-left corners of the b sides.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>Text in good condition.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>


                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="23" n="mistara"> Written in 1 column with 23
                           lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand
                           guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="inkBlack inkRed"> Written in
                        clear black nasta‘līq with red subheaders. </handNote>

                  </handDesc>
                  <additions><lb/>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label> The <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                        to="Inner_back_cover">left pastedown</locus>: <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca
                        Lindesiana</q> bookplate with pencilled shelfmark <q xml:lang="en">2A</q>,
                     and an earlier Lindesiana label <q xml:lang="en">Additional Persian MSS No. <hi
                           rend="strikethrough">109–110</hi></q>, with the number crossed out and <q
                        xml:lang="en">903</q> written aside. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1775" notAfter="1838">
                        <p>Evidently uniformly bound in a British style in the <placeName
                              cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                              key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</placeName>, together with
                              <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_26541"
                                 ><idno>Persian MS 903</idno></ref>, a three-volume
                              <title>Akbarnāmah</title> (ٍ<ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7305"
                                 ><idno>Persian MS 799</idno></ref>–<idno>801</idno>), and a
                              <title>Maʼās̲ir al-‘Umārā</title> (<ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7332"
                                 ><idno>Persian MS 824</idno></ref>).</p>
                        <p>Sewn at four stations on recessed cords together with endpapers of the
                           same stock as the volume itself, which indicates then-recent manufacture.
                           Edges trimmed and spattered borwn, and front-bead endbands yellow and
                           green silk threads twined at <locus from="Head" to="Head">head</locus>
                           and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus>, one missing. Covered in
                           full dark red goatskin <material>leather</material>, tightbacked, and
                           tight-jointed.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Board edges tooled with solid and dotted diagonal
                           lines in gold. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">Spine</locus> panels
                           paletted with meanders and single fillet lines either side, and titled <q
                              xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">TAREEEKHI ALFY</q> along with the volume
                           number at bottom.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>344</height>
                              <width>270</width>
                              <depth>62</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>In fair but stable condition with bumbed headcaps.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Probably completed in the <origPlace cert="high"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</origPlace>
                     <origPlace cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001518">Bombay
                        Presidency</origPlace> undated, but probably <origDate cert="medium"
                           calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1818" notAfter="1847">1818–1847</origDate>
                     during the tenure of physician <persName role="fmo"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/74205978" key="person_74205978">James Bird
                        (1897–1864)</persName> in the Bombay Medical Service where he also also
                     served as Secretary to the Bombay Asiatic Society and published works on
                     various historical and archaeological subjects related to India. After his
                     return to Britain, he opened a medical practice in <placeName
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                        >London</placeName> then sold his manuscript collection through the firm of
                     <persName role="auc" key="person_157917019">S. Leigh Sotheby and John
                        Wilkinson</persName> on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1856-07-10">10
                           July 1856</date>, where an individual named <persName>Hetchley</persName>
                     purchased it for £3 5 shillings.</origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Subsequently acquired by <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                           >London</placeName> bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                              (1819–1899)</persName>, who then offered it for sale in his <date
                                 calendar="#Gregorian" when="1865">1865</date> catalogue, no. 843, for £5,
                        before he sold it to <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058">Alexander
                           Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> on 10 Oct. of that
                        year for the the <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552"
                           key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall,
                        <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384"
                           key="place_7010384">Wigan</placeName>. </p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                              calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                                 ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                                 Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                           Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                              >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                                 ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                        <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                           key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
